  "review": "Told from the future, an animated prologue informs us that after a lengthy conflict, a vampire uprising was quashed by warrior priests and humankind is now safely ensconced in walled citadels ruled by the all-conquering religious regime.\nUnfortunately, though chief monsignor Christopher Plummer denies their existence, the bloodsucking blighters are thriving in the wastelands outside.\nThis comes to the attention of righteous brother Paul Bettany when lawman Hicks (Gigandet) arrives from beyond the walls to tell him that his farmer brother (True Blood star Stephen Moyer in a little casting jape) has been attacked and his niece Lucy (Collins) has been abducted by slimy, eyeless marauders.\nBlood being thicker than holy water, ‘Priest’ is compelled to break his vow of peace. At the price of excommunication, he resolves to go forth, prove Pope Plummer wrong and help Hicks get the girl.\nNaturally, there are many obstacles in their path, from Brad Dourif’s sneaky charlatan and the vampires' barely human ‘familiars’ (imagine a sickly-looking Right Said Fred tribute band) to what appears to be an angry cross between a blind Rottweiler and a walrus.\nLuckily, they find an ally in Maggie Q's combative clergywoman who was sent by Plummer to bring her old colleague back. Thanks to their shared history, she proves sympathetic to his cause.\nAfter much razzing across the desert on their Tron-style jetbikes, the trio realise that the kidnap was just part of a revenge plan dreamed up by fallen Christian soldier Karl Urban, who fell into vampire clutches in the opening scene.\nSo expect an almighty showdown as Legion director Stewart takes his cue from The Matrix and Mad Max 2 to bring this post-apocalyptic crusade home.",
